    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-10-14T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-10-14T08:00:00-05:00" n="575"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d575">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/3058</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-10-14T13:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 14, 1916, 1 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 5.20 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>5021. From my conferences on the black list, it has occurred to me that possibly
                    I may secure its removal in the following way:</p>
                <p>The British to withdraw the whole American list since it gives us annoyance which
                    they did not intend nor wish to give us.</p>
                <pb facs="0743" n="457" xml:id="pg_457"/>
                <p>We, on our side, grant the British Government’s legal right to forbid its
                    subjects from trading with their enemies wherever domiciled. This I understand
                    is the French law and I am told that this principle has been affirmed in a
                    decision of the Supreme Court of Massachusetts.</p>
                <p>If I may personally and informally suggest this plan, the British Government may
                    express a willingness to accept it. If they do, you can then instruct me
                    officially to propose or accept it. Please telegraph me whether this meets with
                    your approval.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
